<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="166" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,1556,2087]" lastBlockId="6.[136,1452,158,292]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="166" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,312,1556,1582]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Description:—</emphasis>
Shrubby 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[416,478,1556,1582]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">habit</emphasis>
, 
<quantity box="[495,639,1556,1583]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="15.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="m" value="0.95" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.4">0.40–1.50 m</quantity>
high (
<figureCitation box="[716,808,1556,1582]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,229,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[153,1430,548,1958]" captionTargetId="figure-214@3.[138,1449,533,1978]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Opuntia tehuacana. A. Shrubby habit, 1.20 m high. B. Defined trunk, grayish scaly bark with light brown tones. C. Juvenile cladode, prominent tubers, areolas with short yellowish trichomes. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413806" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413806/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Defined 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[931,999,1556,1582]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">trunk</emphasis>
, 
<quantity box="[1016,1088,1556,1583]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="35.0">35 cm</quantity>
in diameter, grayish scaly bark with yellow tones (
<figureCitation box="[360,450,1592,1618]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,229,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[153,1430,548,1958]" captionTargetId="figure-214@3.[138,1449,533,1978]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Opuntia tehuacana. A. Shrubby habit, 1.20 m high. B. Defined trunk, grayish scaly bark with light brown tones. C. Juvenile cladode, prominent tubers, areolas with short yellowish trichomes. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413806" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413806/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). Glabrous 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[588,706,1592,1618]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">epidermis</emphasis>
, irregular epidermal cells, slightly sunken parasitic stomas (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[136,229,1965,1987]" captionTargetBox="[273,1326,894,1915]" captionTargetId="figure-50@8.[215,1371,870,1940]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Maximum credibility phylogram of clades, using Bayesian inference of Opuntia s.s. species and related groups. The phylogenetic position of O. tehuacana and O. olmeca is shown in bold. The support of clades is represented by a corresponding thick line with subsequent Bayesian probability PP ≥ 0.95." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413824/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 6F</figureCitation>
). Subcircular to slightly obovate 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[545,648,1628,1654]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">cladodes</emphasis>
, some elliptic, 
<quantity box="[822,934,1628,1655]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="24.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="19.0">19–30 cm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity box="[1024,1135,1628,1655]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="20.0" valueMax="24.0" valueMin="16.0">16–24 cm</quantity>
wide and 
<quantity box="[1254,1380,1628,1655]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="1.35" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="1.2">1.2–1.5 cm</quantity>
thick, green in color, covered with a light layer of wax, evident podaria (
<figureCitation box="[897,986,1664,1690]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,229,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[153,1430,548,1958]" captionTargetId="figure-214@3.[138,1449,533,1978]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Opuntia tehuacana. A. Shrubby habit, 1.20 m high. B. Defined trunk, grayish scaly bark with light brown tones. C. Juvenile cladode, prominent tubers, areolas with short yellowish trichomes. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413806" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413806/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1008,1098,1664,1690]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Areoles</emphasis>
arranged in 5–6 series, 
<quantity box="[1374,1451,1664,1691]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="3.4">3.4 cm</quantity>
separation between series, 
<quantity box="[436,512,1700,1727]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="2.5">2.5 cm</quantity>
separation between areoles, elliptical, large 0.5 × 
<quantity box="[1074,1153,1700,1727]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="0.3">0.3 cm</quantity>
, blackish, short trichomes. Generally scarce, short (
<quantity box="[413,546,1736,1763]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="0.35" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.2">0.2–0.5 cm</quantity>
), yellow glochids arranged at the top of the areola. 1–7, white-grayish, flexible 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,209,1772,1798]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">spines</emphasis>
generally with some yellow spines, slightly subulated, twisted, adpressed, diffuse, and erect, unevenly 
<quantity box="[1348,1451,1772,1799]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" metricValueMax="5.8" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="3.4" valueMax="5.8" valueMin="1.0">1–5.8 cm</quantity>
long. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[200,410,1808,1834]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Juvenile cladodes</emphasis>
with prominent tubers, areolas with short yellowish trichomes, subulate, erect, green leaves, at the basal part and reddish apex, yellow spines (
<figureCitation box="[710,803,1844,1870]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1887,1909]" captionTargetBox="[167,1427,206,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[138,1449,190,1863]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Opuntia tehuacana. A. Subcircular to obovate cladodes. B. Parasitic stomas, isodiametric, multicellular epidermal cells. C. Flower bud, top view. D. Acute flower buds, reddish perianth segments, subcircular pericarp. E. Subcircular, green fruit. F. Longitudinal cut of the fruit, wide walls, white funicles with reddish tones. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413810" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413810/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Acute 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[899,1041,1844,1870]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">flower buds</emphasis>
, yellowish-green perianth segments with mucronate apex, obovate pericarp, raised tubers, areolas with short trichomes, whitish color, yellow glochids, and areolas with yellow bristles (
<figureCitation box="[461,650,1916,1942]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1887,1909]" captionTargetBox="[167,1427,206,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[138,1449,190,1863]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Opuntia tehuacana. A. Subcircular to obovate cladodes. B. Parasitic stomas, isodiametric, multicellular epidermal cells. C. Flower bud, top view. D. Acute flower buds, reddish perianth segments, subcircular pericarp. E. Subcircular, green fruit. F. Longitudinal cut of the fruit, wide walls, white funicles with reddish tones. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413810" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413810/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Figs. 2B and 2C</figureCitation>
). Red, orange, and yellow 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[952,1039,1916,1942]" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">flowers</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1055,1143,1916,1942]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1784,1806]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,332,1744]" captionTargetId="figure-87@6.[138,1449,317,1759]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Opuntia olmeca. A. Shrubby habit, 1.00 m high. B. Defined trunk, grayish scaly bark with light brown tones. C. Juvenile cladode, prominent tubers, areolas with short yellowish trichomes. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413814/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
), 6.0– 
<quantity box="[1214,1290,1916,1943]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="7.2">7.2 cm</quantity>
long, obovate pericarp, ca. 3.8 × 
<quantity box="[345,423,1952,1979]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="4.7">4.7 cm</quantity>
, areolas arranged in 2–4 series, spaced 
<quantity box="[863,953,1952,1979]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="0.96">0.96 cm</quantity>
apart, with crass basal scale, outer segments of obovate perianth, mucronate apex, smooth, yellow edges, with medium greenish striation, reddish apex (
<figureCitation box="[1351,1437,1988,2014]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1784,1806]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,332,1744]" captionTargetId="figure-87@6.[138,1449,317,1759]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Opuntia olmeca. A. Shrubby habit, 1.00 m high. B. Defined trunk, grayish scaly bark with light brown tones. C. Juvenile cladode, prominent tubers, areolas with short yellowish trichomes. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413814/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
), oblanceolate inner segments, retuse, yellow apex, smooth upper edges (
<figureCitation box="[933,1017,2024,2050]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1784,1806]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,332,1744]" captionTargetId="figure-87@6.[138,1449,317,1759]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Opuntia olmeca. A. Shrubby habit, 1.00 m high. B. Defined trunk, grayish scaly bark with light brown tones. C. Juvenile cladode, prominent tubers, areolas with short yellowish trichomes. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413814/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
), stamens 1/3 of the length of perianth, greenish-yellow filaments, yellow anthers (
<figureCitation box="[631,723,2060,2086]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1872,1894]" captionTargetBox="[153,1428,201,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-23@7.[138,1448,190,1847]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Opuntia olmeca. A. Elliptical cladode. B. Parasitic stoma, isodiametric, epidermal cells with a multicellular aspect. C. Flower bud, top view. D. Acute flower buds, green perianth segments with reddish apex, obovate to elliptical pericarp. E. Yellow flower in anthesis. F. Side view of the flower, outer segments of obovate perianth. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413816" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413816/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="165">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
), cylindrical style, ca. 
<quantity box="[985,1063,2060,2087]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="5" pageNumber="165" unit="cm" value="1.8">1.8 cm</quantity>
long, white, 8–12 yellow to light green papillary stigma lobes, ca. 
<quantity box="[500,575,158,185]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="166" unit="cm" value="0.4">0.4 cm</quantity>
long. Elliptical to obovate, green 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[950,1015,158,184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="166">fruits</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1029,1115,158,184]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1872,1894]" captionTargetBox="[153,1428,201,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-23@7.[138,1448,190,1847]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Opuntia olmeca. A. Elliptical cladode. B. Parasitic stoma, isodiametric, epidermal cells with a multicellular aspect. C. Flower bud, top view. D. Acute flower buds, green perianth segments with reddish apex, obovate to elliptical pericarp. E. Yellow flower in anthesis. F. Side view of the flower, outer segments of obovate perianth. Photographs by Martínez-González." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413816" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413816/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="166">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
), 
<quantity box="[1134,1258,158,185]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.95" metricValueMax="4.2" metricValueMin="3.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="166" unit="cm" value="3.95" valueMax="4.2" valueMin="3.7">3.7–4.2 cm</quantity>
